  "prompt": "Do restaurateurs have any clues as to when a Michelin inspector is dining in their restaurant?",
  "response": "Michelin inspectors are trained to be highly discreet and go to great lengths to maintain their anonymity. They typically:\n\n1. Pay their own way\n2. Book under false names\n3. Pay with cash or credit cards that don't reveal their identity\n4. Dress like ordinary diners\n5. Never identify themselves to restaurant staff\n6. May visit a restaurant multiple times before writing a review\n\nRestaurateurs generally have no reliable way to conclusively identify a Michelin inspector during a meal. The goal is to ensure that every guest receives the same high-quality service and experience. Any special treatment would defeat the purpose of an anonymous, objective review.\n\nSome top restaurants train their staff to provide exceptional service to ALL guests, which helps maintain consistently high standards regardless of who might be dining.\n\nWhile there are occasional rumors and speculation about potential \"tells,\" Michelin deliberately keeps the identification process extremely secretive to maintain the integrity of their reviews.",
